\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 What were you paid when you were at Parkers as a twister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Well, at - get standing wage it were about - ten - ten shilling, but I could - I could addle -
 up to seventeen shilling, you know, were on a piece, and you had to work at a peak, you didn't get so much you know then. And then - when the second world war - and were getting more money every week, you know, there were so much percent more - of course
 it were going up, going up giving us back you know, debates, and - and then in the second world war, I was still there - and - of course my - youngest boy were born in the second world war, 1916.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 The first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 My - first - no, the second - my youngest. He were born in 1916.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 That was the first world war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Yes. But - he - he - he - the night after he were born - in - 1909 - and our Alfred were - he was seven years old before our Eddie were born, seven years, I'd had two dead babie
s between that. You know. And - when he were born I still went and - I had to go to hospital for have me - 'cos the afterbirth were left and - for a week after I had a terrible time and - and I went to the - had to go to the hospital for - so long but my 
w
ork was all right, and then I went to me work - and when he was six month old my - the war was only you know, I went to Botany, and when - I - when - he went - went to the Botany to work and when - I - I went - when he was six month old my husband got a j
o
b - he - oh he got his papers to report for being a soldier. And he went and he got his shilling. And he come back, they threw him out. They examined him you know. Oh Bright's disease. Anyway - but he got this job as a boss. On munitions. You see he could
n
't go to the war so he had to work on munitions. Well he - it - it's terrible isn't it you know. Anyway he went - he - he went to Vickers, he got a card to go you know from be exchange. And he - he got a job and he had - oh a few men under him, and they w
ere gri}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12541753\charrsid5456321 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
ding - shavings, wire shavings for - they were making guns, you know, these guns for - for war, at Trates Brother, the - the - Bradford, Thornton Road. And so - he - he couldn't keep coming back to Keighley you know, well it were - exhausting, so he
 - he got me to go down there, and I know they paid for it flitting, it were five pound.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 That was to Bradford was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 To Bradford. And - and we got - in a house - facing - the works on Thornton Road ay the end, well near the centre of town, and 
- we were there - 'til - we were there 'til my - youngest boy - and I - I opened a little shop. I had - you know, work and I let my husband, used to - pounds out of the till and gamble it, you know, he - he used to think well - but you - you don't keep a 
s
hop to keep you, you keep the shop, it doesn't keep you. And because Ned were - came to see me, he came to - to get - order some provisions - at - for his shop in Keighley, and - and he said - look sell up, while the going's good and come back home to Kei
ghley. And - and so I did. 'Cos it were in my name.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Was that after the second boy was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes it were just - he were just turned - five then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 It was after the 14/18 war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes. Yes. No the war was on, the first world war was on when I 
went there, yes. He were born, you know, 1916 we went there and he were just - six month old when we went to Bradford. Yes. And - anyway - I worked at the mill then,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12541753\charrsid5456321  I worked Priestl}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 y's on Thornton Road. And - well the working }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12541753\charrsid5456321 girls then, it had been Priestl}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 y and the working girls you know, used to be at Keighley. And I worked there and - I worked there all the time, and still - you know, I had to keep my husband. Because -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Let's just get back to when you worked at Parkers, because that's the place you worked at longest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes, I worked all the time there. See, I came back to Parkers. I come back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 When you started work at first when you were sixteen, at Parkers, do you remember what the pay was then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Well - I had to learn but 'til we 
got - we got a week's wage ordinary you know and it - were about - ten shilling, nine and something I think it were. Yes, well - some didn't flat that, spinners rate and six you know, oh they get -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 It wasn't as good as yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you feel that that was a fair wage or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Well we did then but anyway you know - then start getting the pay when the war broke out. Then you start getting - so much a week, and they got to thirty shilling extra, well - you know - and the people used to be
 saying, well - you should, but they was - taking off us - the upper ten. The - all mill owners is Conservatives you know. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you give any of the money to your mother, in the two years that you were working before you got married and you were still at home?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Oh yes I did, yes, oh yes, I - I gave mother - and - and - I used to give her - she used to - she used to - take it off me, but she used to give me - half crown back. And then I - I used to save it, but that didn't go so far then because 
stuff was - you know - it were cheaper but it weren't as cheap as it was - before, when we were first married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 What would your mother spend it on, the money you gave her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh - my mother shopped, she brought in for the week, she never had to go to the shop for her bits and bobs, she didn't believe in that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So it would go with the general housekeeping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes, it went with the household budget.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 How did you get on with the other people you worked with at Parkers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh I had some good friends at Parker.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 How did your employer treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Well - they used to be jealous, they used to be saying, well he never talks to us like he talks to you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 He was very nice with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh they - yes, he was and he only talked about w
ork, he didn't - you know, and they were always suggesting you - I had a thing with him you know, but - I wouldn't have thought of such a thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 How did you feel about him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh I liked him as a friend you know, but nothing else. And he were a goo
d boss and now young Billy, 'cos he'll tell you now if I went back - I know the - well the - his fore - his charge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12541753\charrsid5456321 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
hand when I went back after me accide}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12541753\charrsid5456321 nt - he hummed and j}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
arred you know, then he said, oh well we'll, we'll send for you. And he went in the 
office to Billy and so Mrs Holis told me and she must have told him - I were there and I had me caliper on, and - and he come out, and so he says to him, called him Routledge you know - him that were manager there, he said, look, he said - you can put tha
t away he said, you can come now if you want, you take your coat off and start now. Yes. So he told - yes, then he got off and he were telling me he had sent for him you know, and friendly because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 That's when you were seventy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes, well I was s
even - when I come out the hos - after me accident. Oh yes, they were very nice to me and - and - of course I did me work and - they could always really on me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you like the work or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes, I did, very much, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 That was your first full time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You worked at Parkers until about 1916?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 And then you went to Botany Wools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes, during the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 And then because your husband had to move to Bradford you took this small shop in Bradford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes. And I worked in Bradford then, just the same in mill you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 As well as having the shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Oh - yes, he - he looked after shop with being poorly you know, and I'd no money they were - everything were dear and I'd two children and you didn
't get money when your children were born, I didn't. I got no help from - only - your pound for maternity - you didn't get what they get now, look at the money they get, it's ridiculous.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So at the end of the first world war you came back to Keighley?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you go back to Parkers again then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes. Yes, I went back to Parkers. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 I think you said in 1939 you went to Days, is that right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 My oldest boy were - my oldest boy - youngest boy'd be about sixteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So that would be 1932?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 In 1932 you went to work as a cook at Days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 And then how long did you work at Days for? About three years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 No, no, I didn't work long and then I went to Mrs Webbers, I - I stayed there a few yea
r - well you see - well they moved to Leeds you know, and her husband - well he died here. They were only retired six month. They all do at the town council don't they, die - they seem to give up and die don't they? I think you do when you give up working
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 How long did you work for Mrs Webber, do you know?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Oh a long time. I - I really couldn't - call it work cos - I used to do cleaning and - used to wash. And she used to say, you're a wonderful woman, and I said, if you send to laundry they woul
dn't be half as nice as that. But then you know she had - but the boys, you see, the washing wasn't always big because they went to - boarding school. Young Phil went to - Giddleswaite, and - young he died - young Jack, he - he went to - Leeds university,
 
and so did Max, Max went there. He went to - and then their - Enid, that were a girl, she was the oldest I think, and then she went - she were at London, in - in a girls - high school, teaching, and - 'course Mrs Webber come from London, she belonged Shep
herds Bush you see. And - and they all made a fuss of me, even to children. They were just like our own, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You were a companion help were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 I were, yes, and - yes, and then I used to - I - I used to go with 'em for the three month holi
day. Used to take me and all and it were lovely, and they used to look after my husband. She used to come - every week in the car to Keighley, and she'd go up to my husband, she'd roast meat and she'd take it, and everything. And she used to get me to bak
e
 for her, bread, plain bread she - 'cos she used to buy a lot of bread you know, she hadn't - and she used to say - I - I wish you would bake - she used to buy the flour and she used to buy mine and all. And I used to bake and bring it back at Monday morn
ing, and it used to be lovely 'cos she - they'd always got bought bread you know from Days. Anyway - she - she were awfully good to me, I never forget her. And - she paid me well more than ever I got there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you work with Mrs Webber until the second world war started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 I worked there about two years. Two or three year and then - I went back to the mill, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You went back to Parkers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Until the war started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 She was sorry I were leaving her but she - she knew I had 
to do, I couldn't - leave my husband, she were good to me and - and she was good to my husband. She - she were more like a mother and - she used to tell me all her troubles you know and the - she was a person you could talk to. You see?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you leave her service because you wanted more money, was that it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Well I had to leave her services because - my husband were getting that ill you know I couldn't leave him - for long and I used to have to do a lot for my children, I couldn't leave them. And you see -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You were telling me that you left Mrs Webber's service about 1934?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes. Thirty - thirty-two or - yes, 34 because - me mother passed over in - 33.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 And you were still there were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You left them because you wanted t
o go back to the mill because the mill was near where you lived and your husband was becoming so ill that you wanted to be near him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes. I had to look after the children and all you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So you went back to Parkers again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you stay at Parkers then until the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
And then - I - I - I stayed - I stayed while the war, you see - when the war ended then the Parker mill started again, it was closed down during the war, the second war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So during the second world war Parkers closed and you went to work on munitions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes. Yes. First world war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 In about 1939?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Yes. Oh I went back about - just after the war, in 1918 was it. I went just after the war ended and I've been there ever since. You see, and - I've just 
- oh this war - this war, and I worked at munitions this war you know. And my boys went soldiering they had to go my boy was exempted his work 'cos he had a good position, and he had to go and - you know, and - he were only a week soldier before he was in
 
the for - firing line. Then he had - he - he were wounded, his arm were blown - blown to pieces but they mended it and chucked him into the - tanks. And it - he had splinters up his - all his fingers were shattered, and - and now it comes up like that som
etimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So after finishing at Prince Smiths on Munitions Parkers opened up again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 And you went back to Parkers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 And you worked there until you were seventy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 'Til I was - I went back after I'd left and - and wor
ked while - while I was seventy-six. 'Til I was seventy-six. Yes. I'd go tomorrow if I could.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Were you still doing full time all that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh no, they wouldn't let - I did half time, they wouldn't let you you know and I paid five}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12541753\charrsid5456321  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 penny stamps, 
because because it counted me pension then, you know, we could only addle so much at first with us pension and we only had about nineteen shillings. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Looking back on your life and at the various jobs you've done, is there any occupation that you w
ould have preferred to have done rather than any of those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
No - no, I don't think I would, I might have gone on the stage if - if I - but I never thought I'd get married, I never wanted to get married. You see, it - a thing that I never wanted to get
 married. I was never - left to - in - to - doing anything of me own you know, and - I was really shielded - in life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Do you think perhaps if you hadn't married when you were eighteen, especially to a man who was sick, do you think you might well have
 tried for the stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Well you see I didn't want to marry him you see but it were all arranged. And I never courted my husband, I never walked him out at all because - he were twelve year older than me you see. And I said - I didn't want to get marri
ed but still I - I always think this, and I've always thought it, well it was my lot. I - I believe you know that our life is planned for us before we're born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 And you made the most of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes, so I made the best of it. Many said I should have l
eft him and - but I couldn't do that. My father used to say although he was against it at first because he didn't know anything about it and it caused a lot of unhappiness in my family but - he - he said two wrongs don't make a right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You served a very short training period to become a twister did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 How long did it take to learn?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Oh it didn't take me long, I seemed to pick it up very quickly. And then when you do that you can do anything, I can do anything in a mill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did it take about a week to learn to be a twister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Oh sometimes it takes a bit more you have to be fast you know. You might be in a hundred and twenty ends - and - and they're double, there's two hundred - two hundred and forty ends and they alw
ays pull down two ends at a time you know and tie knots you know, special knots sometimes - and then you - you have to catch them when they're coming out and try to tie 'em in single you know. Oh yes, it's very tedious job, it takes some - it isn't like t
he spinners, just put your bobbin on and put your other in and your away, piece it up, pull the lap off and - knock it together, but oh, twisting's a complicated.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you ever belong to a trade union of professional organization?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Never. I don't believe in these here - unions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 When you were at work at the mill did you feel that there were divisions of interest among the workers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 They were very nice some of them and there was some very rough. Yes, yes. But still they were very nice people
 I did - I did work among, they did seem to have that rather decent people at Parkers you know. And I - I did work amongst them like friends I had - lots of friends that I meet many a time you know, and they say you never get to look no older, you know, t
h
ey're still you know and I always speak to them, I never look down on nobody because - I - I am nobody really to look down on anybody, I - I think I'm as good as anybody, whether they have all the riches in the world, or whether - and - and I think - you 
know, me friends, I think well if they lived in a cottage or - or - or lived in a humble surroundings, or a mansion, they're still my friends. 'Cos money can't buy everything, it doesn't buy love and it doesn't buy your life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you feel at that time that the employers and workers had the same interests or different,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Oh a lot of 'em had - yes, a lot of 'em, I know a lot that has - has done well for theirselves. In marriage you know, they've married someone and they've - gotten on - you wouldn't think that they were the same person.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Some people say that in those days there was a great division between trained craftsmen and other workers, did you feel that or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh no, well you see, it was more in the men. And then of course secretary w
orker such as that, that is mental work isn't it. My oldest boy, that's the only trouble is he said - is sitting - at the desk, is sitting at the desk and - and it's all mental, it's - you know, it's - makes your head bad, but he's a good memory, it's a g
ood job he has. But I wouldn't have liked that job you know myself. No. I think it's - well he get - I think sometime it's a lazy job, it's just mental.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Would you say that full time work changed your general attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 No, I liked it and I liked the people I did, I liked all - well you have to be if you want to be happy and content.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 I'd like to ask you about your life at home after you left school and before you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you continue to live at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 I've always lived at home. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did starting full time work change your relationship with your parents at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Well no, you see, I - I was - you see, I - I - I used to - I - it's like a void there you know, my mother was ill but - still -
 you see, when I were seventeen - sixteen really - seventeen or sixteen my mother was ill - and - and then I went to the mill you know. And - 'course - me father used to always say that it's something better for me but I - I said I don't believe in - show
i
ng them into something - that - that they don't want. I didn't do that with my boys, they - they've - stepped out on their own and they've done well, you know, I let them go to an easy job at first, one went to the shop and - and - well the other went to 
school at Bradford and then he - you see, he went and got the job himself in an office and - he were a chauff}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12541753\charrsid5456321 eur for his mas - his boss, Mr S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 ugden, and used to go buying and selling with him, and go to Glasgow and he used to stay overnight. But - you see - I gave them that opportunity, I missed. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Would you say that you still got on quite well with your parents once you started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh - yes, I loved my parents, and they loved me. But they were strict and all that but I - I - I - I - I tha
nk them from the bottom of my heart. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you spend your Sunday any differently, did you still go to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes, and I used to have to go to Sunday school, three times a day, Sun - Sunday morning, Sunday afternoon and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 After leaving school you still continued to do this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes, I did, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you take any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Never. I didn't get interested at all in politics,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You didn't take any interest at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You told me earlier something of how you spent your spare time, you used to be in concerts and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes, I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 And you used to read a bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes, I love reading.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You used to help your mother about the house, did you continue to spend your spare time in thi
s way or did you do things differently now, did you do different things once you'd left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes, we had just our ordinary work to do, I still had work to do and - and - in fact - things like that and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you still go walks with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes, I went with my father a great deal. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 And cycling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Oh yes, used to take me to Ripon races and - yes, he were lovely. But - I had a lovely childhood, you know, and I - when I see some fathers and mothers I can't understand t
hem. You know. Because I love my children, I do now, I love - me grandchildren as well. But I - I think - a mother's love is sacred.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you get to go out in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 I never got to roam the street, I never - I - I had to be in summertime - 
when I got older I had to be in by half past seven - eight o'clock, we had to be in home an be in bed by nine. Yes. My boys had, up to them getting married. My husband used to lock the door - he said, if you're - not here when - at a certain time, the doo
r
'll be locked. And he used to do, he'd lock it if - but they never did and he - when - when they were courting he - my oldest boy well were twenty-six nearly before he were married, and - and - my youngest boy come in you know and he never bothered about 
g
irls, well her were - well he were - he were same age a him, and he - he said, there's our Alfred - at the end of - street, he says, talking to a girl. So - his father went out and he shouted at him. He said, here, don't stand at street corners, he said, 
c
ome in here. Of course he were - old enough then you know. And - and - anyway she came in and - didn't get married for about two year, they got engaged then, and - and - they didn't get married for - for about two years, and - they're sweethearts and they
'
re still sweethearts they don't bother to sit down and plan their money like I used to do, although I addled it, I used to sit with my husband and plan my money. That day. And it was - I know me uncle and - they used to say, she gives her husband her mone
y, you know, playing pop with it. They hurt me but I didn't care. And - he - he - I said, we don't - we plan it, I said, and what's mine is his and what's his is mine but we never had nothing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you make any new friends once you started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes, plenty of friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 New ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes, you do, you do meet a lot, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 How did you meet them, did you meet them at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes, I met 'em at work and there were some nice girls that worked at - down in the winding and that and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Where would you go to with them, when you went out with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Well we may have a - a trip you know, we'd go to Blackpool for a day or Morecambe, but - you see - it never bothered me didn't much like that. And - when my hus - husband were living you 
know - we had three cars. Yes. And - we used - well we used to learn - lend Mr Ford of one - for he used to lend it out, you know, for - well it were a Armstrong Siddley, it were sixteen horsepower. And - but you could run them then for - lot cheaper now.
 
Were only five shillings a gallon weren't it, the petrol. And it - it - when - when I get home at night sometime if - in summer, you know, when we're married and - he'd say, come along and - get our Alf to come and drive the car, 'cos he were a lovely dri
v
er my husband. And - both my boys - have had cars. My youngest boy, his son has one now. Our Alfred says there's no pleasure on the road, and - he says he - get - say, take us to Morecambe. Well it used to be only half a crown to Morecambe then you know. 
For the day.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Was this between you leaving school and being married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes. Yes, I were married then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 But before you got married, when you were still at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh I didn't have much - but we used to go
 trips you know. We used to go to Cleethorpes and Scarborough, with mother - with mother and father, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did your parents meet your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 A few of them. But you know, I never had really a constant companion, only a cousin. They called her
 Parker. And - and she used to be on the stage with me and we - used to call us night and day, she was - dark, right dark, right brown eyes and bright black hair, and I were fair. And they used to call us night and day. But - I never had - I never - had a
 companion, not what you'd call a companion - we used - we used to have little secrets you know, same as girls do, but - we never told them. We could keep one another's secrets, you see. And - well up to her passing I was - good friends with her, yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did they expect to know where you were when you went out, your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did your parents expect to know where you were going?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes, I had to tell them where I was and everything, and where I'd been when I got back and what I'd been doing. Oh yes. Oh I had -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You had to be in by nine o'clock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Oh yes, there were no - after - in summer and - in winter it was seven o'clock many times. And since I've worked - when I were married it would be like that me and my children. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You were married when you were eighteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You hadn't done any courting before you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 I never courted my husband.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 How long did you know him before you married him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 I knew him - he'd only been to our house onc
e and my father gave him a bed. A wood bed, a good wood bed, there weren't - weren't such things as wood beds hardly then. And of course that's the - of course the - the - one of the committee men told him - well he were - yes. But my father didn't know h
im and - and then his sister come and met me mother you know and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So you met him through your mother and his sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Where did he come from, was he a Keighley man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes, he were born in Adelaide Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 How long was it between your mother arranging this marriage and you actually marrying him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
It weren't long, I know I didn't want to get married. You know, I was just beginning to live, I hadn't had much - like - well I don't - life - well - well of course in that day th
ey had - they had - they weren't children when they were fourteen were they. They kept the children as children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Why do you think it was that your mother wanted you to get married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 I don't know, you - my mother thought it best, she used to say, 
well - you know, he - he's a bit older, she said, but you know - he - he'll look after you, she thought that I'd be looked after you know, 'cos you know - it - it were a real - he were a clever man in his mind you know. And he wasn't a man that cursed and
 
- was a - but he liked to go with his - these better end people, what they called better and - them that had money to spend and burn I called it, and - he had - he - he - he - he'd go with them and - and they'd have beer, or - or liquor you know, well the
s
e gentry do, in - he'd go with them up and down, and he'd come home and you couldn't tell - he were drunk. That - he were - but - but when - next morning he - his - his eyes is like that, you know, he'd long tapered fingers he hadn't hands like a man that
 worked hard does. He right - well - lovely hands, lovelier than my hands, and white and beautiful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You'd told me that you had a hundred and odd pounds when you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 What? Yes. Yes. Well that money bought cars and my husband - he bought c
ar - had to buy cars 'cos you could get a car then for - a hundred pounds couldn't you. And a good car.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 He bought a car with the money?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 I bought my husband a car, bought him a lorry. To - oh - they would - he didn't hawk it, it was all ordered,
 and then you see he couldn't do it, he had a do at - at - at Skipton, and the man he had working for him, he had to pay him, I didn't get any}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12541753\charrsid5456321  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 money. And then - he bought him home this day, were a specialist in - Skipton, and - he said, oh it were terrible
. He started in the cab - he were - he never drove with - that's why - he didn't - drive - the last - I mean, yes, because he - you see, he used to have these bleeding does and - oh it used to reach ceiling at house, nearly, like a fountain. Doctor Link s
aid he didn't know where it had come from.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 This money that you had - you'd saved it up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes, well I - I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Before you knew you were getting married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Spent on my husband and doctors for him, specialists and - it were no good. Well I know
 it weren't but I - I just did me best for him and showed him I were trying to make him well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did your parents help you in setting up a house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Me - me mother - me mother did at first, you know. But we'd - but my husband bought a leather suite, y
ou know, and then - some - some of the money I had - I went and I - I - I - I bought a - a - and then we got a piano, little piano you know and my husband were a good player and - he could play any instrument, so could my boys, me eldest - me youngest boy
 plays - he's a lovely player.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Were you sort of engaged or did you just get married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 No, I were just - it was just like a - arrangement, a - a business arrangement as I call it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Can you describe the wedding, what it was like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh it was quiet, we just went in - with - them there witnesses and come out. The Registry Office. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So you didn't have a special dress or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 No, I didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you have any presents or guests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes, I got - I did receive presents af
ter, but you know after we got married, but you know they all played on - you know, I got married - and - and - well people could send because - when I was young I was - rather nice looking.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 And they thought you could have done better?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Did you have a honeymoon at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Where did you live after you married? Did you not move very far from your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 We went to live with his sister. But - my - mother didn't like it but she used to come and she used to bring us 
things you know and they used to be waiting of course, they used to share.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 How long did you live with his sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Well I - I was there while my boy was born. And - and when my boy - was about three month old - then mother said, well this isn't g
oing to do, and she said - she talked to us like, she - we went to see her, and - she said, this isn't going to do, she said, you - you're better in a house of your own. And - he got a house further on the street you know, went and applied for it, it was 
e
mpty, it was a nice house - it were three and seven a week, and it were a nice house, there were two bedrooms, and the - me mother had it done through for us and - and everything and it were nice and - and - my - my boy was born there, well just according
 my mother said - well he - you - me - me oldest boy were born with his sister, but - youngest boy were born there. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So you stayed there until you went to Bradford did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 It was just - and we went there to - he was at Bradford and then whe
n we come back - we couldn't get a house here, it were awful to get an house you know. And anyway we - we went to live over - you know Harrison}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12541753\charrsid5456321 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 s used to have a chemists shop in Lowe Street, over the Arcade there, by Butterfield}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12541753\charrsid5456321 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
s, well - my - my mother and - and me cousin was - they went down there, they heard about this - flat you know, and - and they went, it was a pound a week. But it was beautiful. Beautiful, and I'd been used to things like that you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 That was the end of the war was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh that was the end of the war and my boy was - he was - just turned five, he went to - school, he was seven, he'd be seven. Me youngest.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So for most of your married life until the end of the war you lived at Adelaide Street did you say it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 No, down the village, Louisa Street. Oh well we - oh we lived in Belgrave Road, we lived in Belgrave Road twelve years nearly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 But before 1919 where did you live mainly then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 19? Oh in Fruit Street, that when I first married you know. Yes. And our - our A}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12541753\charrsid5456321 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 fred - our Alfred were born in Fruit Street. They were both born in Fruit Street. Mm. In the village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Your husband was twelve years older than you so he must have been about thirty when you married him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes, well he wasn't quite thirty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 What was his job when you actually married him, was he working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
He were a - a - a - a foreman in the carding, the combing. Designer, and - and then he drove a motor you know for Conyers carriers, he used to go - companions with Conyers, their son. But - and he worked for them - driving their motor car.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 How long had you been married when he finished work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Well they were - I - I hadn't been married long, when - when he started - with this - Brithts disease. Kidney trouble, he nearly
 collapsed in his - well he went about with - couldn't get 'em off for a month.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So he had kidney disease and asthma?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Mm. Brights disease and - and bronchial asthma.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So how long did he work after you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh he didn't work muc
h, he just - worked while the war were on a bit you know and then he - he - he went back to Botany, and then - he - he didn't work - well he were - he didn't work - while my children were growing, I had to keep them, I had to keep him and all, he never ke
pt me. But I didn't mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You always had to find the money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 I always had to work. Yes. And - and nobody couldn't come as - they could come and say I owed 'em a ha'penny.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 As a foreman in carding and combing if he had worked how would presumably have earned quite a decent wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Oh he had a good wage during the war, when he were foreman - of the war, but I didn't get it. He used to sometime work all night. He could - he could stand it, I - and then he'd come home then and - and he'd be li
ke this here with his shoe - couldn't get his breath, it were terrible. He used to make me -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So you never got anything out of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Never got no wage off him, my husband, anybody'll tell you. His sister said I wouldn't live with him. He used to -
 I used to spend me own money. And if I was a penny short and I couldn't - and I would go to Co-op, I used to go to Co-op in Belgrave Road, and I'd - I'd - I'd - go and order me groceries and I'd pay for them. And do you know, I'd come home and - and he'd
 
have me arranged up and I'd have me Co-op cheque there you know, we got cheques then, and he - he's say, you're a ha' - you're - a ha'penny short. And I know one day, oh he did get in, he made me poorly you know. I were like a child, and he said - I said,
 
well I don't know where it is, and I'm putting all this away and he come - and then I went back to the cupboard, and it were the salt, you know, I'd put it straight in the cupboard instead of - in - in a box I had, instead of - leaving it on the table wit
h the groceries for him to reckon up. He said, you're a ha'penny short. That - a ha'penny. But it had nothing to do with him really, were me own money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 How did he feel about you having to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 I - I've always liked work, I've never been - I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 How did he feel about it? How did your husband feel about you having to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh, he did - he thought I had to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 He thought it was all right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes, he didn't bother 'cos - I were getting looked after. But he - he - when he come to
 - lie - the eleven - just twelve weeks before he died, he used to - he used to say, you have been good to me. And he used to say I'd get somebody else you see and - I said, oh no, I'm a one man woman, I don't want no men. I said, I've finished with men. 
'Cos I never slept with my husband for twenty-five year after that I catched him with that woman you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 That was about 1916 when that happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes. Just - just before my boy were born, a month before he - my youngest boy were born. I never fo
rget him, although he swore and he'd get on his knees there were - nothing here and I said, well I said, I don't believe you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So you felt he was carrying on with other women?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh I did, she were no good either, she were a prostitute.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So you never slept with him again after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
No. No. But I never left him, he had his good points. But I couldn't forgive him that. No, 'cos - I mean I didn't bar him from anything, you know, I - I was his wife. And - and - and all - what - what things are but - I couldn't forgive that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 You wouldn't marry again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
No. I could have had chance to marry a stockbroker. But I wouldn't - it's not so long since, asked me ever so many times, I said, no. I said, you have a son. He said, my son'll be a mill
ionaire when I die, he said, but I should leave you all right, and he's as old as me. Well I mean - perhaps two year older than him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 But you've had enough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh I did. And you see we're still good friends, I said, all right, yes, you can still be friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 How do you think your husband felt about his work, did he like it or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
Oh yes. Oh yes, they liked him at work. He was a very - he - you know - after he met my par - parents, he got right reserved. You know, it - it - in a way 
he started going their way. 'Cos he used to say, I wish your father and mother were here, he said, because, he said, they learnt me a great deal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 So you had two boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 One was married in 1909?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 And the other was married in 19 -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 One was born in 1909?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 And the other was born in 1916? Between those two you had two still born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Were your children born at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh yes, they didn't - only when I had me youngest boy - they 
rushed me to the hospital you know 'cos the damage and - then the afterbirth had been fast you see. And - oh he got it away, the doctor, but - six hours and he said I'd have been a dead woman. It were me mother that sent him, she saw - she saw the af - sk
i
n from the afterbirth you know and - she right straight away for him to come at once, she were - come to my house and she - she bathed him down there after the nurse, the nurse, I had a nurse like - proper nurse and - and - not a midwife, she were a prope
r
 nurse and - and he said - she said - tell him to come at once and when he came - he knew, he had an idea, but thought it - if she'd have seen to me, the nurse, it would have come away, and he - he wanted - I know - he wanted some condis fluid, and this s
i
ster says, oh I have some - she brought in a medicine bottle - anybody could drink this you know, four hour - for - every four hours. And - got his coat on, he had his case and everything with him, 'cos I suppose mother had told him, but she had another n
a
me for it, right big word you know, well I never learnt them things you know. But she called it what she called it. And - she - how she knew when she bathed me down there you know she sponged me, and - and she bathed me down there and when I - of course I
 
lost such a lot of colour you see, and she - she - I had to be stitched you see, after - Alfred and then it - of course it broke away when I had the second child you see. And the - and - and - he - he - he had got - they'd gotten his shoulders through, ou
r
 Edward - his - his - his head and then the shoulders wouldn't come, and doctor had to put some more - on, and - and - and - he said - to the lady next door, he said, when - when I say pull he said, pull my shoulders, and he was pulling him tell you. Oh I
 
- I had me legs tied - tied up to the bedrail. Oh yes, and - I didn't - he said you've been a right brave little lass the doctor - Doctor Dalby said, and so - anyway when he were - when - I had to go to the hospital for sixteen week. Oh yes, because - I'd
 lost such a lot of blood you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5909703 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Would it also be because you were in a fairly run down condition due to having worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3691612 MM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 Oh well you see, having the - the afterbirth being there - you see, and she hadn't seen to me, and he told her not to take 
a lying in woman again. And - anyway - and me mother you know, she told him, she said, well I - I was bathing her, I saw this - hard skin like bladder skin you know, and she said, I tried to pull it and she said, oh she nearly went crazy. Mother, she said
,
 you're - you're pulling me inside out. And she left it, she knew then - but she didn't tell me what it was you know, she knew what it was. But she - said to me it's afterbirth. And it had - it had broke. After - when they were pulling the - the shoulders
 
out you know it had broke. And - it were a good job that - it didn't break when the baby was in birth or it would have smothered him you know. And it would have killed me and all I fancy. Anyway, I could feel him, he had to work his hand up me inside, and
 I wasn't under an}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11809149\charrsid5456321 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13971545\charrsid5456321 
esthetic, he put me - no, he - put his hand - worked his hand up and - and - this were about - three days after I were - and I - I - I think I were dying, me mother came and she said - I - I said oh mother - and she were going, well I thi
nk I'll go now. And she said - I - I said, oh don't leave me mother. I said, I - I - I - I'm dying, I'm sure. I felt to be floating on the bed you know. And she - nearly had a fit you know, and she - oh she did, she stopped and then she had the - the - it
 were the afterbirth that were - you want it taking away, yes, so - so when he come he had to work his hand up - and he brought it away and he said - yes, he said - it were all there. But he said he knew but he said, if - if she'd have syringed -
